@node "Release" "Release notes"

@{b}Dear Amiga Folks@{ub},

I believe this is a surprise for to see SysPic release after over 4 and half
years  since  it's  last  release.   It's  not  new  release  but  just free
re-release of the same version.

    First  of  all  I  want to say big THANK YOU to all those who registered
SysPic.   In  total  there  were  about 100 (one hundred!) registrations!  I
believe  that  was  quite  a lot, considering that only after one week since
4.00  release  a pirate keyfile appeared on the net.  Even now, after such a
long time, I am receiving e-mails with questions about SysPic registration.

    Here goes a long story...  Just after I released original SysPic 4.00 in
September  1996 I moved to Warsaw to continue my studies in computer science
at Warsaw University.  That was tough time for me - I had to make up for the
differences in courses.  Also, shortly after I moved to Warsaw, I met a girl
(and  got  some real life ;-) so in the effect I didn't have time for Amiga.
After  first  academic  year  in  Warsaw  facing  very  difficult  financial
situation  I had to get a job.  So I became even more busy.  By the way, I'd
like  to  admit  that  during  my  first year in Warsaw the money I got from
registration helped me to feed myself.  Really.

    In  fact,  during all this time I was naively thinking that I would find
time  to  work  on SysPic.  I even wrote an update with enhanced random file
selector  and support for playing long sound samples using asynchronous I/O.
That  was  about  in  summer  1997.   But I didn't find time to debug it and
release.   One  year  later in summer 1998, wanting to keep my promise about
buying  a graphics board I bought one, hoping that finally I would manage to
find  time  for  another  release  that  time with CyberGFX support.  I even
started to work on that, downloaded required libraries and stuff.  But...the
fate continued.

    I  remember  that for some reason I wanted to read some files from Amiga
harddrive under Linux on an Intel box I bought in meantime.  Something (now,
years  after then, I know it was Windoze) corrupted RDB of the harddrive.  I
managed  to  fix  it  except  I  lost my highly customized system partition.
Without  it  I  could  not do anything and I didn't have time to recreate it
from  scratch.   Fortunatelly  I  did  not  lost everything including SysPic
sources.   After  the RDB was corrupted I made copied the image of the Amiga
drive  on  Intel PC.  That was just in time because few hours later, while I
was  playing  to  repair  RDB  the harddrive...  passed away.  So I ended up
without  harddrive  for  my  Amiga.  Eventually I restored the system from a
friend's harddrive, but again I became so busy with my work and studies that
I could not find time for SysPic.

    Last two years I was busy working on my MSc thesis.  In meantime I spent
one  year  abroad (in United States) on an internship doing research towards
my degree.  I graduated month ago, in March.  I thought it's highest time to
do  something  for  the  abandoned  Amiga community and finally release free
SysPic.

    I  will no longer support SysPic, neither Amiga.  With this release that
wonderful  time  with  Amiga  time is finally over.  But perhaps SysPic will
find new home?  Please @{"read this" link Author}.

    Yours sincerely,

    @{b}Grzegorz@{ub}

@endnode

@node "Author" "Author"

SysPic  has been written by Grzegorz Calkowski.  I can be reached via e-mail
at @{b}grzes@calkowski.net@{ub}.  

I  have  set  a  home  page  devoted to my past Amiga products where you can
download  SysPic,  including  it's old versions and some other support files
and  programs:  @{b}http://www.calkowski.net/amiga@{ub}.  Note:  this page may be not
available during upcoming few weeks due to server reorganization.

@{b}IMPORTANT NOTICE:@{ub}

SysPic  is  looking  for  a new maintainer.  This version of SysPic has been
released  under  @{"GNU General Public Licence" link Copying}.  You can find full source code
of  SysPic on Aminet (util/boot/SysPic400src.lha).  If you wish to take over
SysPic development please contact me!



@endnode

