@node "Intro" "Introduction"

@{u}@{b}Introduction@{uu}@{ub}

    If  you  think that black screen during boot time is boring and you want
to  make  the  boot  process  look  more  professional (or even fancy) it is
definitely  program  for you.  I know there are other similar programs - but
SysPic's  features  make  it  absolutely  the BEST!  Just take a look at the
features list :)

    SysPic  is  a  small  but  powerful  viewer-like program meant to show a
picture  during the boot time.  The picture can be removed at any time using
an  separate  command  (@{"ClosePic" link ClosePic}) which  can  be placed for example in your
WBStartup drawer.

    Features - SysPic 4.00               * - a star feature :-)

      o is small & VERY fast! (picture decompression routines written
        in optimized assembly)
    
      o shows IFF-ILBM pictures of any size and resolution,
        supports AGA modes (also HAM8)

      * has a flexible script-like language which allows you to display
        configurable text with hard/soft info, also with typewritter and
        shadow effects

      * can display a realtime digital clock on the displayed picture

      * can fade-in picture and fade-out it to Workbench (with selectable
        rate) - this works in asynchronous manner (i.e no delays) -
        mouse pointer is also faded

      * can play IFF-8SVX samples or Protracker modules with volume slide
        synchronized to fade-out

      o centers picture both horizontally & *vertically*

      o centers the mouse pointer when exits

      * has a very powerful random selector - an option assures that
        a picture won't show twice until all pictures are shown

      o forces Workbench to open behind the displayed picture so it can be
        closed after whole Workbench initialization, also works with
        the Directory Opus 5, the Workbench replacement

      o has no problems with MCP 'PubModes' feature

      * is iprefs-jump proof - sets overscan prefs before IPrefs will do it!

      o picture can be displayed in a desired mode or just promoted to
        specific monitor

      o optionally blanks the pointer sprite so you won't see it when the
        Workbench screen opens (it would look annoying) (see @{"Bugs" link Bugs})

      * picture is automatically closed when something goes wrong with
        booting - when an requester pops up on Workbench or so

      o detaches from shell in an intelligent way (i.e after loading
        the picture)

      * DOES NOT fragment the memory!!!

      o has been thoroughly tested by a team of betatesters

@endnode

@node "Require" "Requirements"

@{u}@{b}Requirements@{uu}@{ub}

    SysPic  requires  at  least Kickstart 3.0 (no chance for 2.04 compatible
version,  sorry).  Memory requirement depends on size and no.  of colours of
displayed picture.

    To  play  Protracker  modules  @{"ptreplay.library" link ptreplay}  v6.5+ is needed.  It is
included in the package.  The library isn't needed if you don't want to play
modules.
@endnode

@node "Install" "Installation"

@{u}@{b}Installation@{uu}@{ub}

    It's  fairly  easy.   First step is to copy files in appropirate places.
There  is  the  Installer  script  provided.  Just click on 'Install SysPic'
icon.

    If  you  prefer  to  do it by hand first copy file 'SysPic' wherever you
want.   I  recommend  you to put it to C:  or somewhere else on your command
path.  Note, that there is 68020 version supplied.  Use it if you have 68020
or higher CPU.

    In order to remove opened picture, the small program @{"ClosePic" link ClosePic} is
needed.  Simply drop it to 'WBStartup' drawer.

    If  you  use  'FadeIn' option the tool @{"WaitForFadeIn" link WaitForFadeIn} is needed.  Copy
it also to C:.  There are some @{"other tools" link Tools} included.

    The  second  step  is  to modify the startup-sequnce.  @{b}Just add one line
right after SetPatch command:@{ub}

        @{i}SysPic <file> <options> @{ui}

    Options  are  described in @{"Usage" link Usage} section.  @{"Here" link startup} you can see an
examplary outline of a customized startup-sequence.
@endnode

@node "startup" "Customized startup-sequence"

@{u}@{b}Customized startup-sequence@{uu}@{ub}

;
; the startup-sequence
;

C:SetPatch QUIET

DEVS:Monitors/Multiscan         ; load monitor we need for syspics
SysPic <picture> <options>

....commands before IPrefs....

; Please comment/remove the monitor load sequence - it's slow and
; does redunant work - why to create monitor list you use on
; every boot? The only benefit it has is that it automatically
; loads every file in DEVS:Monitors. But do you often change it?
; Therefore it is better to execute them.     
;
DEVS:Monitors/PAL
DEVS:Monitors/NTSC
;DEVS:Monitors/Multiscan        ; NOTE! We have already loaded it!!
DEVS:Monitors/DblPAL
DEVS:Monitors/DblNTSC
etc.

;IF EXISTS DEVS:Monitors
;  IF EXISTS DEVS:Monitors/VGAOnly
;    DEVS:Monitors/VGAOnly
;  EndIF
;
;  C:List >NIL: DEVS:Monitors/‾(#?.info|VGAOnly) TO T:M LFORMAT "DEVS:Monitors/%s"
;  Execute T:M
;  C:Delete >NIL: T:M
;EndIF

....more commands before IPrefs....

C:WaitForFadeIn            ; this line is required if you use @{"FadeIn" link Usage} option
C:IPrefs

....etc.....


    Now see @{"Usage" link Usage}.
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"

@{u}@{b}Usage@{ub}@{uu}

    The  main  program - 'SysPic' can be used only from Shell.  It makes not
much  sense  to  use it from Workbench (for what ?).  Therefore don't try to
launch  it  from  WB because it will do nothing (at least it won't crash the
machine).

    Well,  in  fact,  SysPic  is  a  full-featured  viewer.  It's capable to
display  any  ILBM  image  upto  256  colours  and HAM6/HAM8 images as well.
Currently  no  CyberGFX  support. It uses custom IFF
parsing routines, written in optimized assembly (i.e faaast :).

    The options template for 'SysPic' looks like:

Filename/A,RandMin/K/N,RandMax/K/N,Digits/K/N,Dir/S,EX=ExRand/S,
BF=BestFit/S,SO=SetOscn/S,KP=KeepPtr/S,VC=VCenter/S,BB=BBlank/S,Public/S,
ST=Sticky/S,NF=NoFrag/S,ModeID/K,Monitor/S,FadeIn/K/N,FadeOut/K/N,
R=Red/K,G=Green/K,B=Blue/K,Delay/K/N,Sound/K,Rate/K/N,Volume/K/N,Module/K,
Filter/K,Clock/K,H12/S

Huh, a little complicated?  :) Don't be scared, 'SysPic ?' brings a brief
description instead of the cryptic template.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} Options new in Release 4 are marked with *NEW*

    where

*NEW*   @{b}Filename@{ub} <path>         Specifies the filepath for an IFF-ILBM
                                picture or SysPic script. See description
                                of the script commands. Note, that
                                'Filename' keyword can be omitted.

                                Note, this option used to be 'Picture'.

                                IMPORTANT NOTE: SysPic changes it's current
                                directory to the directory of picture/script
                                given here - so the path for sample/module 
                                can be relative to it.

                                Example. Let's say we have in RAM: two files:
                                mod.song and picture.ilbm. 
                                
                                C:> SysPic ram:picture.ilbm module mod.song

                                The above will work.

        @{b}RandMin@{ub} <number>        SysPic 2.x style random selection
        @{b}RandMax@{ub} <number>        See @{"Random selection" link Random}
        @{b}Digits@{ub} <size>             
                        
        @{b}Dir@{ub}                     New random selection method.
        @{b}EX@{ub} or @{b}ExRand@{ub}            See @{"Random selection" link Random}
                        
        @{b}BF@{ub} or @{b}BestFit@{ub}           Switch - if specfied program will use
                                BestModeIDA() function to obtain the best
                                resolution & display mode for the picture.
                                Try it if for some uncertain reasons picture
                                is shown incorrectly.

                                With current implementation this option
                                should correctly display pictures saved in
                                modes like Multiscan, DBLPAL, etc. on
                                PAL/NTSC only configurations. The reverse
                                may not be true.

        @{b}SO@{ub} or @{b}SetOscn@{ub}           Sets your overscan preferences (from
                                envarc:sys/overscan.prefs file). It avoids
                                the very annoying screen-jump when IPrefs
                                sets the overscan prefs. It's practically
                                necessary when you want to display a picture
                                in a hisync mode like DBLPAL or MULTISCAN,
                                which overscan preferences usually differ
                                from the defaults. Note, it's a hack!
                                See @{"Bugs" link Bugs}.

        @{b}KP@{ub} or @{b}KeepPtr@{ub}           Switch - if specified the mouse pointer
                                won't be blanked.
        
        @{b}VC@{ub} or @{b}VCenter@{ub}           Switch - enables vertical centering. Usable
                                for displaying brushes - saves space & time.

        @{b}BB@{ub} or @{b}BBlank@{ub}            Switch - use ECS/AGA blank border option

        @{b}Public@{ub}                  Switch - makes SysPic's screen publically
                                available. It's NOT public by default as in
                                previous releases (2.03 - 2.11).
                                The screen name is 'SysPic' (surprise?).

        @{b}ST@{ub} or @{b}Sticky@{ub}            Switch - SysPic won't exit at keystroke or
                                mouseclick. The only way to get rid of the
                                SysPic's screen is ClosePic command.

*NEW*   @{b}NF@{ub} or @{b}NoFrag@{ub}            Switch - avoid memory fragmentation. All
                                allocations are made on the top of the
                                memory pool (i.e with MEMF_REVERSE flag, for
                                techies). Recommended, but see the note
                                about @{"statram.device" link Tips}.

        @{b}ModeID@{ub} <modeid>         Shows picture in a specific mode. The
                                'ModeID' keyword must be followed by a
                                display id value. If it's hexadecimal no.
                                (usually) it must be prefixed with '$' or
                                '0x':

                                ModeID 0x39024 ;MULTISCAN:Productivity
                                ModeID $89024  ;SUPER72:Super-High Res Laced
                                ModeID 692229  ;DBLPAL:High Res Laced

                                @{"ListModes" link ListModes} tool will reveal these magic
                                numbers to you.

        @{b}Monitor@{ub}                 Switch - if passed only monitor bits
                                are extracted from 'ModeID' value. I.e the
                                picture will only be promoted to chosen
                                monitor. For example, specifying
                                'ModeID $39024' does not imply 'MULTISCAN:
                                Productivity' display mode but only
                                MULTISCAN monitor! If the picture is in
                                lores it will show up in lores, but using a
                                MULTISCAN resolution.

                                This switch does nothing without 'ModeID'.

        @{b}FadeIn@{ub} <rate>           Picture will fade-in from black with
                                specified rate. Legal range for <rate> is
                                1...16. (1-fastest, 16-slowest). Example:

                                FadeIn 16       ; fade-in very slow & smooth

                                NOTE: it won't work with HAM pictures!

                                IMPORTANT: See @{"WaitForFadeIn" link WaitForFadeIn} description.

        @{b}FadeOut@{ub} <rate>          Picture will fade-out to Workbench
                                background color (by default, see below)
                                and then Workbench will be faded-in.
                                Rate range as above.

                      
                                
        @{b}R@{ub} or @{b}Red@{ub}                Specifies the colour to fade out to (and to
        @{b}G@{ub} or @{b}Green@{ub}              fade in Workbench from). Valid range is
        @{b}B@{ub} or @{b}Blue@{ub}               0..255.  Also hex values are accepted (when
                                prefixed with '$' or '0x').
                                @{u}The range is also true on OCS/ECS machines!!@{uu}

                                Examples:

                                Red=0xff Green 0 Blue=0    - bloody red
                                R 255 G 0 B 255            - musashi violet
                                R=0 G=0 B=0                - funeral black
                                Red 200                    - ???

                                NOTE: if you omit a component it's value is
                                taken from the Workbench background pen! I.e
                                'Red 200' modifies only red gun to 200 dec,
                                leaving green and blue untouched!

        @{b}Delay@{ub} <ticks>           Wait for specifed number of ticks before
                                showing/fadeing in the picture.
                                1 second = 50 ticks. Example:

                                Delay 25        ; wait for half a second                                

*NEW*   @{b}Sound@{ub} <path>            Sample (IFF-8SVX or RAW) to play, currently
                                max. size is 128kb for mono samples, twice
                                for stereo samples. Mono samples are played
                                on both speakers. If 'fadeout' option
                                specified sample is synchronously slided
                                down. Loops are supported.

*NEW*   @{b}Rate@{ub} <value>            Play rate for sample (in Hz).
                                May be useful for RAW samples.

*NEW*   @{b}Volume@{ub} <value>          Play volume for sample. Range 1..64.

*NEW*   @{b}Module@{ub} <path>           Protracker module to play. @{"PTReplay.library" link ptreplay}
                                is required. During fade-out it's volume
                                also is slided down.

*NEW*   @{b}Filter@{ub} <ON|OFF>         Turn on or off audio filter. Works also
                                without 'Sound' or 'Module' options.

*NEW*   @{b}Clock@{ub} <clockstr>        Show realtime updated digital clock on
                                the displayed picture. The 'clockstr' has
                                following format:

                                x/y/pen/name.font/size/shadowpen/shadowlen

                                The last two are optional. Use them if you
                                want to have shadowed clock. Examples:

                                Clock 20/10/3/Courier.font/13
                                Clock 20/10/3/Courier.font/13/2
                                Clock 20/10/3/Courier.font/13/2/3

                                If you omit 'shadowlen' the default is 1.
                                BUGS: the 'shadowlen' must be positive,
                                unlike as in the 'SHADOW' script command.

                                NOTE: the coordinates are relative to
                                top-left edge, not to the font baseline.

*NEW*   @{b}H12@{ub}                     Switch - 12-hour style clock


@{b}NOTE:@{ub}  When the picture is shown pressing left mouse button cause immediate
quit, while the right mouse button acts like 'ClosePic'.  This is usable for
tests, to see the fadeout and/or 'exit' part of script.

@endnode

@node "Scripts" "SysPic's Scripts"
@next "Random"

@{u}@{b}SysPic's Scripts@{uu}@{ub}

    The  scripts  are  major  new  feature  of  4.00 release, which allow to
specify SysPic options in file and, using some simple commands, to show some
text  with  system  info on displayed picture.  The scripts consist of three
basic parts: options section, init section and program sections.

The outline looks like:

SYSPIC          ; must be on the beginning (0 offset)
<options>       
...             
INIT:           
<init section>
...
MAIN:                           ¥
<main section>                   ¥  
...                               > program
EXIT:                            /  sections
<exit section>                  /
...

Comments are allowed anywhere when preceded with a semi-colon (;).


        @{" Options section " link scr_options}
        @{" About the commands " link scr_about}
        @{" Init section " link scr_init}
        @{" Program sections " link scr_prog}
          @{" Text printing commands " link cmds_print}
          @{" Text control commands " link cmds_ctrl}
          @{" Other commands " link cmds_other}
        @{" Special values " link scr_special}

The scripts are really easy.  Just take a look at these examples:

       @{" Demos.readme " link Demos/Demos.readme/main}

       @{" Amiga.script " link Demos/Amiga.script/main}     @{"run me!" system "C/SysPic Demos/Amiga.script"}
       @{" Amiga2.script " link Demos/Amiga2.script/main}    @{"run me!" system "C/SysPic Demos/Amiga2.script"}
       @{" AWS.script " link Demos/AWS.script/main}       @{"run me!" system "C/SysPic Demos/AWS.script"}
       @{" A-Start.script " link Demos/A-Start.script/main}   @{"run me!" system "C/SysPic Demos/A-Start.script"}
       @{" Clock.script " link Demos/Clock.script/main}     @{"run me!" system "C/SysPic Demos/Clock.script"}
       @{" Joke.script " link Demos/Joke.script/main}      @{"run me!" system "C/SysPic Demos/Joke.script"}
       @{" Windoze.script " link Demos/Windoze.script/main}   @{"run me!" system "C/SysPic Demos/Windoze.script"}

@endnode

@node "scr_options" "Options section"

@{u}@{b}Options section@{ub}@{uu}

    All  command-line  options  can  be  used  here and they can be split in
several  lines.   The options here take precedence (i.e override) over these
specified  on  command-line.  However, random selections options are treated
differently,  i.e  they  are  independent  from these on command-line.  This
means  you  can  randomly select a script, which again can randomly select a
picture!  :-)

    Note,  if  you  want  to  use this feature, you must put the pictures in
other  drawer  than  the scripts if you use pattern random method due to the
cache file '.syspics'.  This will me fixed in near future.

    Note well, scripts cannot be loaded from scripts!  (It would be crazy :)

    Examples:

1. The absolutely minimal script:

SYSPIC
Work:Pictures/Bootpic.iff

2. Another one with more options:

syspic          ; <- case insensitive
Work:Pictures/BootPics/#?.iff dir exrand
fadein 16 fadeout 10
nf vc
@endnode

@node "scr_about" "About the commands"

@{u}@{b}About the commands@{uu}@{ub}

    All commands are case insensitive.  Only one command is allowed at a
line. Need not to be placed at the 1st column.

    Convention used in commands descriptions:

        < > - angle brackets enclose required arguments
        [ ] - square brackets enclose optional arguments
        " " - double quotes indicate strings
        |   - vertical bar separates options from which you can choose
              only one

    Sections starts with a label followed by a colon (no spaces before
it), for example:

MAIN:

tells SysPic that commands after it belong to main section.
@endnode

@node "scr_init" "Init section"

@{u}@{b}Init section@{ub}@{uu}

    This section starts with 'INIT:' label.  If you want to have main
section (i.e use any script commands) this one must be present and must be
at just after options section.

    You put initialization commands here.  Currently only one is defined:

@{b}FONT@{ub} <no> <name.font> <size>

  Assign (and open) font to slot number <no> (valid range: 1..16).
  By default all slots are set to topaz.font 8.
@endnode

@node "scr_prog" "Program sections"

@{u}@{b}Program sections@{ub}@{uu}

    Two program sections are allowed:  'MAIN:' and 'EXIT:'.

    The  main  section  (must  be present, if init section is there) will be
executed  before  showing  the picture.  The picture will be shown after the
last command.  However, it can be shown earlier with 'FADE' command (or it's
alias  -  'SHOW').   This allows you to write some things before showing the
picture and some other when it's already visible.

    The  exit  section,  which  is  optional, will be executed when ClosePic
signals SysPic to remove the picture.  After the last command the picture be
closed/faded-out.    Again,   with   'FADE'   command  the  picture  can  be
closed/faded-out  earlier, while following commands are executed (i.e typing
and fading out at the same time).

    @{u}TO SUMARIZE:  SysPic operates in asynchronous manner, i.e fading and
script executing can happen simulatenously!!@{uu}

    All  program  sections'  commands  are  allowed  both  in  main and exit
sections.
@endnode

@node "cmds_print" "Text printing commands"

@{u}@{b}Text printing commands@{uu}@{ub}


@{b}TEXT@{ub} <"string"> ["right-aligned-string"] [CR]

  Write string on current coordinates and optionally another string aligned
  to the right margin (in fact when the second string is present the
  commands is split in two:  TEXT and RTEXT).  The actual x-coord is
  advanced to the position after printed string, i.e two commands:

  TEXT "Hello"
  TEXT " World!"

  are equal to

  TEXT "Hello World!"

  'CR' switch does the same what @{"'CR'" link cmds_ctrl} command.


@{b}TEXTXY@{ub} <x> <y> <"string"> ["right-aligned-string"] [CR]
                 
  As above, but the string is printed on the specified position.


@{b}RTEXT@{ub} <"right-aligned-string"> [CR]

  As the 'TEXT' command, for only right aligned strings.


@{b}RTEXTXY@{ub} <x> <y> <"string"> ["right-aligned-string"] [CR]

  As above , on x/y position.


You can use some @{"special values" link scr_special} in the strings.
@endnode

@node "cmds_ctrl" "Text control commands"

@{u}@{b}Text control commands@{uu}@{ub}


@{b}CENTER@{ub} <ON|OFF>

  Turn on or off text centering.  Affects only @{"'TEXT'" link cmds_print} and @{"'TEXTXY'" link cmds_print} commands.


@{b}CR@{ub}

  Carriage-return. Just what it says.


@{b}FADE@{ub}

  This is the only command which acts differently in main and exit sections.
  In  main  section  fades/dumps in the picture.  In exit section starts the
  fadeout  (if  applicable,  i.e if 'fadeout' options has been specified) or
  just closes the picture.  This command has alias @{"'SHOW'" link cmds_ctrl 1000}.


@{b}GOTOXY@{ub} <x> <y>

  Sets pen to x/y position.  The 'x' value becomes left-margin for writting
  text (i.e after 'CR' x-coord is reset to this value).


@{b}JAM1@{ub}

  Set 'JAM1' mode (i.e text is printed without background)


@{b}JAM2@{ub}

  Set 'JAM2' mode (i.e text is printed with background)


@{b}LINESPACE@{ub} <n>

  Value to be added to y-coord when going to next line (i.e on 'carriage
  return').  Negative values allowed.


@{b}RIGHTMARGIN@{ub} <n>

  Set right-margin value.


@{b}SETAPEN@{ub} <n>

  Set foreground pen.


@{b}SETBPEN@{ub} <n>

  Set background pen (used in 'JAM2' mode).


@{b}SETFONT@{ub} <n>

  Set current font to <n>.


@{b}SHADOW@{ub} [pen] [length] [OFF]                   @{u}TRY IT!! :-)@{uu}

  Set's shadow text mode. All texts will be printed with shadow in 'pen'
  colour.  The 'length' specifies the shadow length and can be
  negative. Examples:

  SHADOW        - turn shadow on with default values, pen 0, length 1
  SHADOW 2      - turn shadow on, pen 2, default length
  SHADOW 100 3  - shadow with pen 100, length 3
  SHADOW OFF    - turn shadow off


@{b}SHOW@{ub}

  Alias for @{"'FADE'" link cmds_ctrl 1} command.


@{b}TYPERATE@{ub} <n>                                  @{u}TRY IT!! :-)@{uu}

  If  <n>  is  greater than 0 the text will be printed character by charater
  instead of one go.  The <n> means the delay before next character is typed
  (ca.  in 1/100th of second).


@{b}TYPESPACE@{ub} <n>

  Value  to  be  added  to  x-coord  after  each character is typed.  Can be
  positive or negative (negative values allows for reverse typing).
@endnode

@node "cmds_other" "Other commands"

@{u}@{b}Other commands@{uu}@{ub}


@{b}BOX@{ub} <x1> <x2> <y1> <y2>

  Draw a filled rectangle with current pen.


@{b}WAIT@{ub} <n>

  Wait for specified amount of time (100 = 1 second).
@endnode

@node "scr_special" "Special values"
@next "Scripts"

@{u}@{b}Special values@{uu}@{ub}

The  following  values,  when  used  in  strings  will  be  substituted with
correspoding  string.  They are MCP-compatible (at least these, which exists
in MCP).

        %os  - Kickstart Release (e.g 3.0)
        %wb  - Workbench Release (e.g 3.1)
        %ov  - Kickstart Version (e.g 39.106)
        %wv  - Workbench Version (e.g 40.4)
        %tc  - Chip RAM in Bytes
        %tf  - Fast RAM in Bytes
        %tt  - Chip+Fast RAM in Bytes
        %Tc  - Chip RAM in KBytes
        %Tf  - Fast RAM in KBytes
        %Tt  - Chip+Fast RAM in KBytes
        %TC  - Chip RAM in MegaBytes
        %TF  - Fast RAM in MegaBytes
        %TT  - Chip+Fast RAM in MegaBytes
        %pr  - Processor
        %cp  - CoProcessor
        %cs  - ChipSet

        %dt  - dd-mm-yy
        %Dt  - mm/dd/yy
        %DT  - dd-mmm-yy
        %t1  - hh:mm (24-hour style)
        %t2  - hh:mm XM (12-hour style, with AM or PM string)
        %_d  - day (with leading 0s)
        %_m  - month (with leading 0s)
        %_y  - year (2-digits)
        %_Y  - year (4-digits)
        %wn  - abbreviated weekday name
        %Wn  - weekday name
        %mn  - abbreviated month name
        %Mn  - month name

        %%   - single percent (%) sign

        **   - single asterisk (See {"Bugs" link Bugs})
@endnode

@node "Random" "Random selection"
@prev "Scripts"

@{u}@{b}Random selection@{uu}@{ub}

    SysPic  has  a  very powerful and flexible random selector, which can be
used in two ways.

    First  method,  compatible  with  SysPic  2.x,  works by substituting an
asterisk  (*)  in the filename with a randomly generated number within given
range.

    Options:

        @{b}RandMin@{ub} <number>        Lower bound.
        @{b}RandMax@{ub} <number>        Upper bound.
 
                                Both must be specified!
               
        @{b}Digits@{ub} <number>         Specifies length of the inserted number.
                                If char-length of generated number is shorter
                                that it leading zeros will be prepended.

    @{u}NOTE!!   From  version  3.02 options keywords here are REQUIRED!@{uu}  Following
example will produce names from BootPic001.iff to BootPic018.iff:

        @{i}SysPic Work:GFX/Pics/BootPic*.iff randmin 1 randmax 18 digits 3 @{ui}

    This method is simple, but naming all the pictures with the same manner is
very inconvenient - it's hard to identify a picture.  This is why SysPic 3.00
introduces completely new method.

    Now you can specify a DOS pattern for pictures to show.  A picture will be
randomly selected from the files in a directory matching given pattern.  If the
directory contains lots of files this could be slow - but SysPic takes care of
this - the directory is scanned only once and then all matching filenames are
cached in a file named '.syspics'. So remember:

    @{b}1)@{ub} first SysPic looks for '.syspics' file - if found reads it AND @{u}ignores@{uu}
       the given pattern

    @{b}2)@{ub} if not found - scans the directory for matching files and creates
       '.syspics' file.

    @{u}If you add/remove some pictures and/or modify the pattern YOU HAVE TO
REMOVE '.syspics' file!!!@{uu}

    Options:

        @{b}Dir@{ub}                     Switch - enables pattern random.

        @{b}EX@{ub} or @{b}ExRand@{ub}            Switch - enables exclusive mode.
                                This means that no picture will show twice
                                until all of them are shown. However, this
                                requires a write to harddisk - the information
                                about currently shown files is stored in file
                                named '.exdata'.

    Examples:

        @{i}SysPic Work:GFX/Pics/#?.ilbm dir @{ui}

    will show all pictures matching '#?.ilbm' pattern. And

        @{i}SysPic UMDisk:Images/(Girl|Cute|Sexy)#?(.iff|.ilbm) dir exrand @{ui}

    will show all those nice pictures starting with 'Girl', 'Cute' or 'Sexy'
and ending with '.iff' or '.ilbm' suffix.  Furthermore, you won't be annoyed
with a picture showing more frequently than others.  For thorough explaination
of AmigaDOS patterns see AmigaDOS Manual.

    Method shown above unlike it's predecessor doesn't force you to name your
pictures in a number scheme, it's also fast and, at last, gives you the
'exrand' option...
@endnode

@node "Tools" "Included Tools"
@next "Tips"

@{u}@{b}Included Tools@{uu}@{ub}

    SysPic's archive contains following tools:

       @{" ClosePic " link ClosePic}             - closes SysPic's screen
       @{" WaitForFadeIn " link WaitForFadeIn}        - avoids problems with IPrefs when fade-in
       @{" ListModes " link ListModes}            - lists available screenmodes

    and 2 tools taken from the @{"Visage" link Magnus} distribution archive:

       @{" GetModeID " link GetModeID}            - an alternative to 'ListModes'
       @{" UnpackILBM " link UnpackILBM}           - unpacks IFF-ILBM body - SysPic
                                 will show unpacked ILBMs usually faster

    Two last programs are freely distributable and
    Copyright (c) by @{"Magnus Holmgren" link Magnus}

    I included them because, first, the author allows to use them in other
products, second, why to write something what is already written...
@endnode

@node "ClosePic" "ClosePic"

@{u}@{b}ClosePic@{uu}@{ub}

    This  small  program closes SysPic's screen.  Can be used from Workbench
and  Shell,  too.  The former method is recommended - ClosePic should reside
in 'WBStartup' drawer (see @{"Installation" link Install}).

    To  have picture closed when whole Workbench is initialized set STARTPRI
tooltype  to -128.  It assures that ClosePic will be launched last (for your
convinience it is already set to -128 :).  See @{"Tips" link Tips}.

    ClosePic  understands  another  tooltype  -  'DELAY=xxx' which allows to
delay  picture  closing,  where 'xxx' is ticks amount (1 second = 50 ticks).
For example:

        DELAY=150

causes 3 second delay.  This option is unavailable from Shell.
@endnode

@node "WaitForFadeIn" "WaitForFadeIn"

@{u}@{b}WaitForFadeIn@{uu}@{ub}

    'WaitForFadeIn'  checks  wether  SysPic is fading the picture - if yes -
waits until fade-in is finished, if not - exits quickly.

    This  command  is  required when you use SysPic's 'FadeIn' option.  When
SysPic  is fading it's screen and in background 'IPrefs' command is executed
(as  startup-sequence  is  processed  further) the picture flashes.  This is
possible  due to the asynchronous behaviour of SysPic, especially in case of
optimized  startup-sequnces  and  slow  fade  rate.   To  avoid  it  execute
'WaitForFadeIn' just before IPrefs.  See @{"Installation" link Install 53}.

    Note, all the above also applies to FastIPrefs by Hans-W. Schober!

    This command has no options.
@endnode

@node "ListModes" "ListModes"

@{u}@{b}ListModes@{uu}@{ub}

    This  command  (as  it's name suggests) lists id numbers of screen modes
present in the graphics database.  You would need them for SysPic's @{"'ModeID'" link Usage 55}
option.  This command can be launched from Shell and Workbench as well.

    Note,  that 'ListModes' lists only modes with descriptive names (regular
modes).   I.e will not show modeid for MULTISCAN:160x960 HAM Interlaced, for
example.  This is where @{"GetModeID" link GetModeID} command comes handy.
    
    This command has no options.
@endnode

@node "GetModeID" "GetModeID"

    @{b}NAME@{ub}

	GetModeID -- Get screen mode id number.


    @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}

	GetModeID


    @{b}DESCRIPTION@{ub}

	Open an Asl or ReqTools screen mode requester, and print out the
	decimal number for the selected screen mode. Only the number is
	printed, making it suitable for "backticking" it into the command
	line of other programs.


    @{b}EXAMPLE@{ub}

	A bit useless perhaps, since Visage have a mode requester (among
	other things) already, but just an example to show how it can be
	used:

	Visage Pics:Some.Pic MODE `GetModeID`

    -----------------------------------------------------------------

    Even more useless example with SysPic (but you may use it to find
    suitable mode for a picture):

    SysPic Pics:Some.Pic ModeID `GetModeID`

@endnode

@node "UnpackILBM" "UnpackILBM"

    @{b}NAME@{ub}

	UnpackILBM -- Unpack IFF ILBM pictures.


    @{b}TEMPLATE@{ub}

	UnpackILBM FROM/A,TO


    @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}

	UnpackILBM [FROM] <Source> [TO <Dest>]


    @{b}DESCRIPTION@{ub}

	Unpack the so called BODY chunk of an IFF ILBM file. The BODY chunk
	contains the actual picture data. The other parts of the file are
	simply copied.


    @{b}OPTIONS@{ub}

	FROM	The picture to unpack.

	TO	The file to unpack to. If not specified, then the unpacked
		file will overwrite the original (via a temporary file).
		Specifying the same file for both FROM and TO causes an
		error.


    @{b}FUTURE PLANS@{ub}

	Several things could be improved, including buffered I/O (and thus
	not loading the entire BODY chunk into memory and unpack it there);
	a chunk filter (to remove unwanted chunks). Other (less likely to
	be implemented) things include the possiblity to add/change some
	chunks and pack the BODY chunk.

@endnode

